sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583113
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Inducible arabinose promoter controlling expression of BFP_SpyCatcher_His.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Max van
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: These part was synthesized as linear DNA and only restriction/ligation was done to insert this into the backbone.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The start condon of SpyCatcher and the stop codon of BFP needed to be removed to ensure that one complete protein was expressed.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583017
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Biobrick part BBa_K592100 of the 2011 iGEM Uppsala team, without stopcodon.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Max van 't Hof
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Part was developed by iGEM11_Uppsala-Sweden. It was produced by synthesis of part BBa_K1583113
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The original stop codon needed to be removed to be able to attach SpyCatcher and His-tag.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583061
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This RBS was used in our constructs Mfp5+CsgA and CsgA+Mfp3. CsgA is a protein monomer which can aggregate to form amyloid nanowires in natural biofilms taken from E.coli K-12 MG1655. Inspired by mussels, the Mfp5 (mussel foot protein) has high adhesive properties towards wet polar surfaces. This DNA was synthesized. The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1] 1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The DNA was synthesized. The sequence originates from the genomic DNA of E. coli K-12 MG1655 (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/949055). The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1] 1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The design was based on the paper "Strong underwater adhesives made by self-assembling multi-protein nanofibres".[1] 1. C.Zhong, T.Gurry, A.Cheng, J.Downey, Z.Deng, C. Stultz, T.Lu, Nature Nanotechnology, 2014, 9, 858-866.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: SX scar
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: XbaI/SpeI mixed site. Simply used to aid in entry of parts into the registry.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: pBAD
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: pBAD is an E.coli promoter that is induced by L-arabinose. K206000 is a mutagenized pBAD promoter that is responsive to lower concentrations of arabinose than wild type (I13453) and, additionally, exhibits a higher maximum of protein expression as measured by coupling to a fluorescent reporter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Amelia Hardjasa
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The sequence was obtained by applying all mutations that upregulated AraC binding and subsequent promoter activity listed in reference [1].
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: There were no special design considerations.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583054
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Non-coding scar site in between RBS and gene
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: CsgC is positively involved in the extracellular aggregation of CsgA into amyloid nanowires (curli assembly) in E.coli functioning as a chaperone for CsgA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Stefan Robert Marsden
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The RBS and CsgC were synthesized from the genomic sequence of E.coli K-12 MG1655. The promoter is part of the constitutive promoter family made by John Anderson from iGEM Berkeley 2006.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We inserted non-coding scar sequences after the promoter and RBS to prevent missing initial codons during transcription/translation.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1583018
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: SpyCatcher is a protein that can spontaneously form covalent isopeptide linkages with it??s counterpart `Spytag` under physiological conditions.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Max van 't Hof
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
This gene was synthesized as part of biobrick BBa_K1583113. The idea of using Spytag/SpyCatcher was based on the paper "Programmable biofilm-based materials fromengineered curli nanofibres"[1]
1. Nguyen, P. Q., Botyanszki, Z., Tay, P. K. R., & Joshi, N. S. (2014). Programmable biofilm-based materials from engineered curli nanofibres. Nature communications, 5.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Startcodon was not included, since BFP (BBa_K1583017) was placed in front of this biobrick.
